                <created>Wed, 26 Apr 2023 06:36:20 +0000</created>
                <updated>Fri, 20 Sep 2024 06:02:52 +0000</updated>
                            <resolved>Fri, 20 Sep 2024 06:02:52 +0000</resolved>
                                                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>1</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="428599" author="adilger" created="Fri, 20 Sep 2024 06:02:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t think it is reasonably possible to implement this in checkpatch.  We need to use __uXX variables when working with any variable/structure related to the network protocol and for variables/structures related to the on-disk storage, config logs, etc. &lt;b&gt;in addition&lt;/b&gt; to anything related to the user interface.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Distinguishing between these cases in the code would IMHO be impossible to do in checkpatch.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;While it is true that &quot;uXX&quot; is used in the kernel-internal code and &quot;_&lt;em&gt;uXX&quot; is used for disk/userspace, they boil down to the same 32-bit variable type, so there is no real harm or benefit to change them, besides the savings of two &quot;&lt;/em&gt;_&quot; characters, which are not in limited supply, and possibly a shortening of a few lines.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                    </comments>
